{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 14:40:01.051446", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report\\nNetwork / scope\\n- Topology: multi‑tier Clos (fat‑tree) using EBGP (FRR). Super‑spine (AS 65000) peers with all spines. Each spine peers with leaves in its pod. Leaves advertise host /24s via BGP.\\n- Hosts visible in lab: pc_0_0, pc_0_1 (and other PCs shown by reachability probe).\\n- Devices inspected: leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0.\\n\\nExecutive summary / health\\n- Data plane: host-to-host reachability is normal — ICMP tests show 0% packet loss and low RTTs across tested hosts. No observable forwarding failure during tests.\\n- Control plane: partial BGP control-plane failures are present. Specifically, spine_router_0_1 is not forming BGP sessions with its neighbors (leaves and super‑spine). Several BGP neighborships involving AS65101 appear to be down/active/idle states.\\n- Impact: traffic still flows (redundant paths via other spine(s) are taking traffic), but redundancy and intended topology participation of spine_router_0_1 are impaired — reduced resilience and possible asymmetric/less optimal routing.\\n\\nObserved anomalies and evidence\\n1) spine_router_0_1 has no routes and no established BGP sessions\\n- From spine_router_0_1 show summary:\\n  - \"BGP table version 0\"\\n  - \"RIB entries 0, using 0 bytes of memory\"\\n  - All configured neighbors show State \"Idle\" / \"never\" and PfxRcd 0 (i.e., no established EBGP sessions).\\n  - Example lines (abbreviated): \\n    - Neighbor 172.16.0.2 (AS 65000) ... never  Idle  0\\n    - Neighbor 172.16.0.41 (AS 65200) ... never  Idle  0\\n  - These indicate spine_router_0_1 is not exchanging routes with super_spine or leaf routers.\\n\\n2) Neighboring routers show attempts to peer with that spine but no session\\n- super_spine_router_0 summary:\\n  - Neighbor 172.16.0.3 (the spine_router_0_1 router-id/IP) shows State \"Active\" toward super_spine (super trying but session not established).\\n  - Example line: \"172.16.0.3 ... Active 0\"\\n- leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 summaries:\\n  - Both leaves show a neighbor entry that is in State \"Active\" for the AS expected for spine 0_1.\\n  - leaf_router_0_0: neighbor 172.16.0.40 remote-as 65101 — State/PfxRcd: \"Active 0\"\\n  - leaf_router_0_1: neighbor 172.16.0.42 remote-as 65101 — State/PfxRcd: \"Active 0\"\\n  - These \"Active\" states mean TCP BGP connection attempts are being made but the TCP/BGP handshake is not completing.\\n\\n3) Configuration mismatch on spine_router_0_1\\n- Running configuration for spine_router_0_1 shows:\\n  - \"router bgp 65701\" — local AS number is 65701 in that router\\'s config.\\n- Neighboring devices (leaves and super) expect the spine to be in AS 65101:\\n  - Leaves configured their neighbor to remote-as 65101 (e.g., leaf_router_0_0 neighbor 172.16.0.40 remote-as 65101).\\n  - super_spine and the rest of the fabric use AS 65101 for that spine (consistent with naming in other router configs).\\n- Thus spine_router_0_1\\'s configured local AS (65701) does not match the AS expected by its intended EBGP peers (65101). This causes remote-as mismatches and prevents EBGP session establishment.\\n\\n4) Additional neighbor IP index mismatch (configuration inconsistency)\\n- leaf_router_0_0/0_1 neighbor IPs targeting the spine appear to be .40/.42 (configured on the leaves), while spine_router_0_1 shows neighbor entries with addresses .41/.43 (in its running configuration). This suggests neighbor IP/peer-address configuration is also inconsistent by one address in some neighbor statements.\\n- Evidence (examples from configs):\\n  - leaf_router_0_0: neighbor 172.16.0.40 remote-as 65101\\n  - spine_router_0_1: neighbors include 172.16.0.41, 172.16.0.43 ... remote-as 65200/65201 etc.\\n- This IP mismatch would also prevent a session (peers are pointed at different IPs), so there appear to be two independent configuration problems: wrong local AS and inconsistent neighbor IP usage.\\n\\nCorrelated observations (why data plane still works)\\n- spine_router_0_0 has fully established BGP peers and shows RIB entries and prefixes, and the super_spine has established BGP sessions with other spines. The fabric therefore retains connectivity via the remaining correctly functioning spine(s), which explains why pings between hosts succeed and show no loss.\\n- BGP summaries:\\n  - spine_router_0_0 summary: shows peers established and prefixes exchanged.\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 and leaf_router_0_1 both have other spine peer(s) that are up and providing routes.\\n\\nProbable root cause(s)\\n- Primary root cause: misconfiguration on spine_router_0_1 — its BGP autonomous-system number is configured as 65701 (typo), while peers expect AS 65101. This mismatch prevents EBGP sessions from forming.\\n- Secondary/root-concurrent cause: neighbor IP/peer-address mismatches (off-by-one addresses in neighbor statements) between spine_router_0_1 and leaves (leaves point at .40/.42 while spine lists .41/.43), which would also prevent TCP/BGP adjacency even if AS numbers were correct.\\n- The two misconfigurations together explain why super_spine and leaves see \"Active\" or \"Idle\" states toward that spine and why that spine has RIB 0 and no prefixes.\\n\\nImpact assessment\\n- Immediate: spine_router_0_1 is not contributing to the control plane — it does not learn or advertise prefixes; any traffic that would have used it will be rerouted via other spines.\\n- Network resilience: reduced — loss of a spine\\'s BGP adjacency reduces path diversity and may increase load on the remaining spine(s).\\n- Service: current host-to-host connectivity remains functional (no packet loss observed), but the topology is not operating as intended and is susceptible to further single-point failures.\\n\\nRelevant excerpts (evidence)\\n- spine_router_0_1 running config: \"router bgp 65701\" (local AS is 65701)\\n- spine_router_0_1 summary: \"BGP table version 0\", \"RIB entries 0\", neighbors in State \"Idle\" / \"never\" (no prefixes)\\n- super_spine_router_0 summary: neighbor 172.16.0.3 (spine_router_0_1) State \"Active\"\\n- leaf_router_0_0 summary: neighbor 172.16.0.40 remote-as 65101 State \"Active\"\\n- leaf_router_0_1 summary: neighbor 172.16.0.42 remote-as 65101 State \"Active\"\\n- Reachability: pings between hosts show 0% loss (data-plane intact).\\n\\nSuggested next diagnostic checks (no remediation steps recommended here; these are additional verification items)\\n- Verify interface IP addressing on spine_router_0_1 and the corresponding leaf interfaces (confirm which IPs should be used for neighbor statements).\\n- Verify the intended AS number for spine_router_0_1 against network design (should be 65101).\\n- Re-run BGP neighbor show outputs after configuration verification to confirm adjacency state transitions.\\n\\nBottom line\\n- The network data plane is currently operational, but spine_router_0_1 has faulty BGP control-plane participation due to configuration errors (wrong local AS and inconsistent neighbor IPs). This reduces redundancy and must be corrected to restore full intended operation of the fabric., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='dcc3ab5c-79f6-4d9a-8e30-da471ba768c9'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
